'''Alan Dean Foster''' is an author of dozens of fiction and non-fiction works and has had his works in more than 100 books. He received a Master of Fine Arts in Cinema from the [[Wikipedia:University of California|University of California]], [[Wikipedia:Los Angeles|Los Angeles]] in [[1960s|1968]]. Foster's writing focuses primarily on science fiction and fantasy genres, although he has had some non-fiction published. Foster has had his works translated into over 50 languages.

In 1995, he wrote the novelization for the [[LucasArts]] video game, [[Wikipedia:The Dig (video game)|''The Dig'']], based on an original idea by [[Steven Spielberg]]. He wrote the novelizations for [[Wikipedia:Star Trek (film)|''Star Trek'']] (2009) and [[Wikipedia:Star Trek Into Darkness|''Star Trek Into Darkness'']] (2013), two films directed by [[J.J. Abrams]]. He also authored the novelization for the first three movies of the [[Wikipedia:Alien (franchise)|''Alien'']] franchise.

==Biography==
He wrote the novelization of [[Star Wars: A New Hope (novelization)|''Star Wars'': Episode IV ''A New Hope'']], as [[George Lucas]]' ghost writer, and the very first [[Star Wars Legends|Expanded Universe]] novel: ''[[Splinter of the Mind's Eye]]''. He later returned to ''Star Wars'', first writing the Republic-era novel ''[[The Approaching Storm]]'', and later the [[Star Wars: The Force Awakens (novelization)|novelization]] of [[Star Wars: Episode VII The Force Awakens|''Star Wars'': Episode VII ''The Force Awakens'']].<ref>{{WebCite|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/04/18/star-wars-celebration-alan-dean-foster-writing-the-force-awakens-novelization?abthid=5532e3d244f2cb2e22000019|text=Star Wars Celebration: Alan Dean Foster Writing The Force Awakens Novelization|author=Osborn, Alex|work=IGN|archivedate=20171020191710}}</ref> and the short story "[[Bait]]" (published in [[Star Wars Insider 162|''Star Wars Insider'' 162]]).

In [[2018]], Foster posted an unofficial treatment for [[Star Wars: Episode IX The Rise of Skywalker|''Star Wars'': Episode IX]] on his website.<ref name="Syfy treatment">{{WebCite|url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/star-wars-writers-predict-how-the-skywalker-saga-will-end|text=Star Wars writers predict how the Skywalker Saga will end|author=Greenberg, Glenn|date=2019-12-10|archivedate=20200925050214}}</ref>

After [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] bought [[Lucasfilm]], Foster stopped receiving royalties from the novels written before the acquisition, including the novelization of the first ''Star Wars'' movie and ''Splinter of the Mind's Eye''. A few years later, the same happened when Disney took control of [[20th Century Studios|20th Century Fox]], and didn't respect the contract between the author and the studio, for which he had written novelizations for the [[Wikipedia:Alien (franchise)|''Alien'']] franchise. In [[2019]], Foster turned to the [[Wikipedia:Science Fiction and Fantasy Writers of America|Science Fiction and Fantasy Writers of America]] Grievance Committee, which tried to settle the dispute. A year later, after encountering strong resistance from Disney, the SFWA decided to go public with the affair. [[Wikipedia:Mary Robinette Kowal|Mary Robinette Kowal]], SFWA's President, commented: "''In my decade with the organization, the fact that we are forced to present this publicly is unprecedented.''"<ref name="SFWA">{{WebCite|url=https://www.sfwa.org/2020/11/18/disney-must-pay|text=#DisneyMustPay Alan Dean Foster|author=Kowal, Mary Robinette|date=2020-11-18|archivedate=20201119010535}}</ref><ref>{{WebCite|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2020/nov/19/sstar-wars-author-disney-royalties-alan-dean-foster|text=Star Wars author appeals to Disney in fight over royalties|author=Flood, Allison|date=2020-11-19|work=[[Wikipedia:The Guardian|The Guardian]]|archivedate=20201123055005}}</ref><ref>{{WebCite|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/11/19/21578621/disney-alan-dean-foster-royalties-copyright-law|website=[[Wikipedia:The Verge|The Verge]]|text=Star Wars Novelist Says Disney Won't Pay Him Royalties it Owes Him|author=Lopatto, Elizabeth|date=2020-11-19|archivedate=20201123173741}}</ref>

